    <header class=3D"prose entry-header">
        <h1 class=3D"entry-title">Easy Permutations and Combinations</h1>  =
  </header>

    <div class=3D"prose entry-content overflow-clip">
        <p>I=E2=80=99ve always confused =E2=80=9Cpermutation=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Ccombination=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 which one=E2=80=99s which?</p>

<p>Here=E2=80=99s an easy way to remember: <strong>permutation sounds compl=
icated</strong>, doesn=E2=80=99t it? And it is. With permutations, every li=
ttle detail matters. Alice, Bob and Charlie is different from Charlie, Bob =
and Alice (insert your friends=E2=80=99 names here).</p>

<p>Combinations, on the other hand, are pretty easy going. The details don=
=E2=80=99t matter. Alice, Bob and Charlie is the same as Charlie, Bob and A=
lice.</p>

<p><strong>Permutations are for lists (order matters) and combinations are =
for groups (order doesn=E2=80=99t matter).</strong></p>

<p>You know, a "combination lock" should really be called a "permutation lo=
ck". The order you put the numbers in matters.</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/2007/02/combination-lock.png.webp" type=3D"image=
/webp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-conten=
t/uploads/2007/02/combination-lock.png" alt=3D"Easy Permutations and Combin=
ations" width=3D"162" height=3D"213" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-=
12468 webpexpress-processed"></picture></p>

<p>A true "combination lock" would accept both 10-17-23 and 23-17-10 as cor=
rect.</p>

<div style=3D"position:relative;height:0;padding-bottom:56.25%"><iframe src=
=3D"cid:frame-135F777692C2C711CFA5875B30D830F5@mhtml.blink" width=3D"640" h=
eight=3D"360" frameborder=3D"0" style=3D"position:absolute;width:100%;heigh=
t:100%;left:0" allowfullscreen=3D""></iframe></div>

<h2>Permutations: The hairy details</h2>

<p>Let=E2=80=99s start with permutations, or <strong>all possible ways</str=
ong> of doing something. We=E2=80=99re using the fancy-pants term =E2=80=9C=
permutation=E2=80=9D, so we=E2=80=99re going to care about every last detai=
l, including the order of each item. Let=E2=80=99s say we have 8 people:</p=
>

<pre><code>1: Alice
2: Bob
3: Charlie
4: David
5: Eve
6: Frank
7: George
8: Horatio
</code></pre>

<p>How many ways can we award a 1st, 2nd and 3rd place prize among eight co=
ntestants? (Gold / Silver / Bronze)</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/math/permuations/permuation_medals.png.webp" typ=
e=3D"image/webp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.com=
/wp-content/uploads/math/permuations/permuation_medals.png" alt=3D"permuati=
on example medals" title=3D"permuation_medals.png" class=3D"webpexpress-pro=
cessed"></picture></p>

<p>We=E2=80=99re going to use permutations since the order we hand out thes=
e medals matters. Here=E2=80=99s how it breaks down:</p>

<ul>
<li>Gold medal: 8 choices: A B C D E F G H (Clever how I made the names mat=
ch up with letters, eh?). Let=E2=80=99s say A wins the Gold.</li>
<li>Silver medal: 7 choices: B C D E F G H. Let=E2=80=99s say B wins the si=
lver.</li>
<li>Bronze medal: 6 choices: C D E F G H. Let=E2=80=99s say=E2=80=A6 C wins=
 the bronze.</li>
</ul>

<p>We picked certain people to win, but the details don=E2=80=99t matter: w=
e had 8 choices at first, then 7, then 6. The total number of options was <=
