/MathML"><mn>5</mn><mo>=E2=88=97</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=E2=88=97</mo><mn>3</mn>=
<mo>=E2=88=97</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=E2=88=97</mo><mn>1</mn></math></mjx-assist=
ive-mml></mjx-container>. What=E2=80=99s another name for this? 5 factorial=
!</p>

<p>So, if we do 8!/5! we get:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/61ecd7fe1d7f131623fd0dcc57f5da0e.png" width=3D"286" height=3D"38=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\frac{8!}{5!} =3D \frac{8 \cdot 7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \c=
dot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}  =3D 8 \c=
dot 7 \cdot 6}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>And why did we use the number 5? Because it was left over after we picke=
d 3 medals from 8. So, a better way to write this would be:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/5b4d125e63d7498f8c3cb318454cf963.png" width=3D"60" height=3D"43"=
 alt=3D"\displaystyle{\frac{8!}{(8-3)!}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>where 8!/(8-3)! is just a fancy way of saying =E2=80=9CUse the first 3 n=
umbers of 8!=E2=80=9D. If we have <strong>n</strong> items total and want t=
o pick <strong>k</strong> in a certain order, we get:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/899fa6e32e1e23123bda5aa00e21a119.png" width=3D"63" height=3D"43"=
 alt=3D"\displaystyle{\frac{n!}{(n-k)!}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>And this is the fancy permutation formula: You have <strong>n</strong> i=
tems and want to find the number of ways <strong>k</strong> items can be or=
dered:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/7164200acc9606cf3547c31ddc023cdd.png" width=3D"146" height=3D"43=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{P(n,k) =3D \frac{n!}{(n-k)!}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<h2>Combinations, Ho!</h2>

<p>Combinations are easy going. Order doesn=E2=80=99t matter. You can mix i=
t up and it looks the same. Let=E2=80=99s say I=E2=80=99m a cheapskate and =
can=E2=80=99t afford separate Gold, Silver and Bronze medals. In fact, I ca=
n only afford empty tin cans.</p>

<p>How many ways can I give 3 tin cans to 8 people?</p>

<p>Well, in this case, the order we pick people doesn=E2=80=99t matter. If =
I give a can to Alice, Bob and then Charlie, it=E2=80=99s the same as givin=
g to Charlie, Alice and then Bob. Either way, they=E2=80=99re equally disap=
pointed.</p>

<p>This raises an interesting point =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99ve got some redund=
ancies here. Alice Bob Charlie =3D Charlie Bob Alice. For a moment, let=E2=
=80=99s just figure out how many ways we can rearrange 3 people.</p>

<p>Well, we have 3 choices for the first person, 2 for the second, and only=
 1 for the last. So we have <mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attach=
ed_0" jax=3D"SVG" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"3" style=3D"font-size:=
 95%; position: relative;"><svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=
=3D"7.667ex" height=3D"1.557ex" role=3D"img" focusable=3D"false" viewBox=3D=
"0 -666 3388.9 688" xmlns:xlink=3D"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidde=
n=3D"true" style=3D"vertical-align: -0.05ex;"><g stroke=3D"currentColor" fi=
ll=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transform=3D"scale(1,-1)"><g data-mm=
l-node=3D"math"><g data-mml-node=3D"mn"><use data-c=3D"33" xlink:href=3D"#M=
JX-TEX-N-33"></use></g><g data-mml-node=3D"mo" transform=3D"translate(722.2=
,0)"><use data-c=3D"2217" xlink:href=3D"#MJX-TEX-N-2217"></use></g><g data-=
mml-node=3D"mn" transform=3D"translate(1444.4,0)"><use data-c=3D"32" xlink:=
href=3D"#MJX-TEX-N-32"></use></g><g data-mml-node=3D"mo" transform=3D"trans=
late(2166.7,0)"><use data-c=3D"2217" xlink:href=3D"#MJX-TEX-N-2217"></use><=
