"31" xlink:href=3D"#MJX-TEX-N-31"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mm=
l unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1=
998/Math/MathML"><mn>3</mn><mo>=E2=88=97</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=E2=88=97</mo><m=
n>1</mn></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container> ways to re-arrange 3 pe=
ople.</p>

<p>Wait a minute=E2=80=A6 this is looking a bit like a permutation! You tri=
cked me!</p>

<p>Indeed I did. If you have N people and you want to know how many arrange=
ments there are for <strong>all</strong> of them, it=E2=80=99s just N facto=
rial or N!</p>

<p>So, if we have 3 tin cans to give away, there are 3! or 6 variations for=
 every choice we pick. If we want to figure out how many combinations we ha=
ve, we just <strong>create all the permutations and divide by all the redun=
dancies</strong>. In our case, we get 336 permutations (from above), and we=
 divide by the 6 redundancies for each permutation and get 336/6 =3D 56.</p=
>

<p>The general formula is</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/677d1e00b27408c0417be10dae451184.png" width=3D"141" height=3D"39=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{C(n,k) =3D \frac{P(n,k)}{k!}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>which means =E2=80=9CFind all the ways to pick k people from n, and divi=
de by the k! variants=E2=80=9D. Writing this out, we get our <strong>combin=
ation formula</strong>, or the number of ways to combine k items from a set=
 of n:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/be21eae92ceda7a78ac8b0042e7b7407.png" width=3D"161" height=3D"43=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{C(n,k) =3D \frac{n!}{(n-k)!k!}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>Sometimes C(n,k) is written as:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/9bbf2e913f973ac6e6043c75a9608e09.png" width=3D"30" height=3D"44"=
 alt=3D"\displaystyle{\binom {n}{k}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>which is the the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_coeff=
icient">binomial coefficient</a>.</p>

